column11: This question was closed on "Alexander Von der Bellen" with an end date of 4 December 2016. Alexander Van der Bellen won Austria's presidential election BBC, Reuters, NPR. See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated

column6: Unless I have seriously misread practically everything, this election is as over as any election could possibly aspire to be. I am glad of the result, although I guessed it dead wrong. (I guessed the US one and several others dead wrong as well, but was not glad. These things happen.)

From FT's (Dec. 6, p.3): "To try to build the Freedom Party's respectability, Mr. (Heinz-Christian) Strache said it would not challenge the result....."No Freedom party members are gathering for demos, no stones will be thrown, nothing is burning - that's democracy" ....
Closed :/

Calculation: Van der Bellen wins the election Alexander Van der Bellen is unobtainable in the election to the German President before his FPÖ competitor Norbert Hofer. This is the result of the ORF calculation of the SORA Institute. According to this, Van der Bellen comes to 53.6 percent, Hofer to 46.4 percent. The first detailed results show that Van der Bellen was able to increase slightly in many municipalities compared to the first election.

Tough one. Most polls (Latest Nov. 17) have Hofer up by 1-3 points. On the other hand most polls were by Gallup which had Hofer up by 6 points ten days before the last election (which ended 50-50). If they have the same bias this time around then A.VdB should win. On the other hand, if the wave of right-wing populism pushes Hofer supporters to the polls in greater numbers, then add another right wing populist to the global cocktail.

The media is talking about this election as if Hofer has already won. I wonder what impact that will have on voters: Will that impel Van der Bellen's voters to go to the polls to prevent what the media is seeming to suggest will happen? make Hofer's supporters complacent and cause the election to go to Van der Bellen? Or will Van der Bellen's voters think "What's the use?" and stay home?

There is a growing trend against the EU and in favor of sovereignty. The establishment rigging of the votes will rally more voters in favor of Herr Hofer. The elite obviously tone death and refuses to change. If you don't adapt, soon you will become extinct.

While generally reported as "too close to call" am confirming the previous forecast. Reasons: - Hofer has consistently polled slightly ahead of Van der Bellen however as mentioned related to the recent US election, polls may be underestimating support for Hofer due to the "far-right" media reports and unwillingness of supporters to be insulted/labelled. - Key issues include immigration (1): Hofer wants to ban economic migrants, while Van Bellen calls for faster integration. A recent report of "sharia police" (2) in Germany suggests integration may be more difficult than Van Bellen suggests. CLIP: " What are the key issues? Hofer has focussed on the EU’s migration crisis and called for a ban on economic migrants. Austria – a nation of 8.7 million – has taken in more than 120,000 migrants from the Middle East, Africa and Asia since last year, bearing much of the burden of the influx together with Germany and Sweden. Van der Bellen has called for faster integration of recognised asylum seekers."
Polls extremely close, last election was extremely close, Hofer has very slight lead in current polls but *also did last time* before he lost narrowly. About as pure a tossup as you'll ever see...

I wish I could come up with a convincing reason to change this, but I can't--unless there is hope in the fact that I have been more consistently wrong about elections this year than in any year since 1956. Stay tuned.

Van der Bellen won the first vote in May by a tight margin. Since then we have seen success for the right with Brexit and the election of Trump. This may have no impact but could swing some floating voters.
Depends heavily on who will mobilize their voters the most. At the moment it seems to be the FPÖ

Polls continue to look very similar to the polls before the previous vote in May when Van der Bellen narrowly won (I won't speculate on whether voting irregularities had any impact one way or another). It's hard to say whether Brexit or the US election will have any impact on anyones voting intentions (my guess would be that it is minimal). As I stated in a previous forecast, the number of votes cast per capita was higher in districts in which Hofer won in the May election. I don't know how this corresponds to actual turnout of eligible voters, but it still suggests that Van der Bellen has a larger pool of non-voters that he has an opportunity to try to turn out for the December vote.
The right-wing party of Hofer has momentum due to Brexit and the Trump victory. His followers are motivated to go to vote.

In three weeks, Austria will go to the polls once more to decide whether independent candidate Alexander van der Bellen or far-right Freedom Party (FPÖ) candidate Norbert Hofer should be the new president.

Polls have consistently (1) shown Hofer ahead with the exception of the Nov 17th (see below.) Poll (Gallup/Österreich) 11/16: Hofer ahead 52/48 Poll (Unique Research/Heute/AT) 11/17: Van der Bellen ahead 51/49 1: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Austrian_presidential_election,_2016

The Austrian Presidential election is being rerun following a very close vote earlier this year, in which Van Der Bellen won. Recent polls indicate a marginal win for Hofer though the result is so close as to be meaningless.

BBC offers background on why Austrian constitutional court annulled the original vote, link here http://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-36681475 "Newsweek" article suggests "far right" candidate of the Freheitspartei, Hofer, is poisted to win the second go-round. Link here http://www.newsweek.com/austria-presidential-election-freedom-party-poll-lead-re-run-far-right-486304

After Hungary and Colombia--these being only the most recent results that were unexpected, at least among me-- guessing about elections seems increasingly like a mug's game. Still, one has to try. On previous form, expect a big win for the Greens in Austria next week.

Austrians fed up with endless campaign as misfires force third vote in tight presidential race Now postponed to Dec. 4, the election was itself a rerun of a spring national vote that was declared invalid after the razor-thin result could not be confirmed amid accusations of vote-rigging. That vote in May, furthermore, was the second round in Austria’s presidential election, meaning Austrians are now preparing to cast ballots for their head of state for the third time.
Taking a clear 2% lead into the election, it would take pulling a rabbit out of the hat to erase that lead

This is going to be a close one. Will have to keep my eye on the polls and betting markets closely. Giving a slight lead to Hofer now given Europe's rightward anti-migrant shift. Also, escalating tensions between Austria and Hungary over migrants might give Hofer an edge by keeping the migrant issue salient. Of course, if Trump loses in the US elections, there might be a backlash against populist candidates in later elections (read in Austria). So, very high level of uncertainty ATM, but going to keep an eye on this one.

Deutche Welle reported that the new election date would be on 04/12 [1]. Wikipedia has a number of polls, the most recent on 24/09, that showed a marginal lead for Hoffer [2]. Polls reported at the end of August had also Hofer in the lead [3] & [4], where it was also mentioned that the undecided were high, but a percentage was not given. Under these conditions, a prediction is particularly hard. The odds appear practically even (accounting for the polls margin of error). Moreover, there is at least two months before the election, with a large number of voters who have not decided, and a significant contributing factor on what to vote for many would be emotional. This means that the result can go either way depending on the candidates' PR tactics and events that happen to take place in the mean time (ranging from the plight of migrants to terrorist attacks), which will affect how many voters will be engaged to go to the ballot box in the first place and then also influence which candidate they will vote. Hence, at this point in time, an equal probability was assigned.
Apparently the election will not upcome until December, but it's unlikely that this will affect the expected result.

assuming "none of the above" means another disputed overturned election, The rise of the right is always underestimated in polls and mainstream analysis (just look at Brexit). This is a close one, since Austria superficially seems less pro-nationalist than other European countries (caveat: I am american and so just going by news articles not experience). Do anti-immigrant voters think the election was stolen by Van der Bellen and now will retaliate? Or do more moderate voters who were on the fence see a close election and decide they will vote against Hofer? Tough to assess the psychology here, but in all giving a slight edge to Hofer.

Van der Bellen won the last election by a mere 31,000 votes. My prediction is that the Trump effect in the US (which right now is looking likely to produce negative results in the polls), and even the aftermath of Brexit, will mobilize more people to support Van der Bellen. Terrorism or further issues with refugees in the country between now and October may give Hofer the edge he needs but I think a lot will depend on the support either candidate may get from the establishment.

The poll published by the Österreich paper on Sunday (31 July) showed the midpoint of the wide range of support for Hofer at 52% — one point higher than a poll in early July found — versus 48% for van der Bellen. https://www.euractiv.com/section/elections/news/right-wing-nationalist-set-to-win-rerun-austrian-presidential-race/
Alexander Van der Bellen narrowly won last time. I think that supporters of the other two main parties are more likely to rally to him this time.

Austria has produced some less than stellar political leaders over the past several decades, starting in let's say April 1889, even when they went for a former UN SecGen. One feels a bit funky predicting that they will not keep up the tradition, so I'll probably start to move up more on Hofer as more polls come in. This is another one where it is important to separate expectation from aspiration.

While his election may not be overwhelming he does seems to have the voting majority agreeing with his policy of restricting further large scale immigration and use of Austria as a transition point into Germany.
